TY  - JOUR
T1  - Characteristics Of Decisional Participation By Nurses
AU  - Alutto, Joseph A.
AU  - Vredenburgh, Donald J.
Y1  - 1977/06/01
PY  - 1977
DA  - 1977/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255408
DO  - 10.5465/255408
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 341
EP  - 347
VL  - 20
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article discusses a 1977 study on the decision-making involvement of nurses in the health care industry. The conceptualization of decisional participation was done by means of a construct contrasting current and preferred patterns of participation in a specific nursing role decisions. The study indicates that individuals desiring more decision-making involvement experienced higher job tension and higher career dissatisfaction. An alternate study found that decision deprivation may be attributed to lower levels of satisfaction with promotion, pay, work, and supervision.
AB  - The article discusses a 1977 study on the decision-making involvement of nurses in the health care industry. The conceptualization of decisional participation was done by means of a construct contrasting current and preferred patterns of participation in a specific nursing role decisions. The study indicates that individuals desiring more decision-making involvement experienced higher job tension and higher career dissatisfaction. An alternate study found that decision deprivation may be attributed to lower levels of satisfaction with promotion, pay, work, and supervision.
