T1  - Genuine Multinational Staffing Policy: Expectations And Realities
AU  - Zeira, Yoram
AU  - Harari, Ehud
Y1  - 1977/06/01
PY  - 1977
DA  - 1977/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255406
DO  - 10.5465/255406
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 327
EP  - 333
VL  - 20
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article discusses a 1977 study on the staffing policy of U.S. multinational corporations. Results indicated that there are several sources of morale problems existing in multinational corporations of the dominant type. These included blocked promotions, transfer anxieties, income gaps, and unfamiliarity and adaptability difficulties. The research also indicates that the accumulation of variegated international experience is not essentially translated into managerial behavior compatible with environmental needs and headquarter's expectations.
AB  - The article discusses a 1977 study on the staffing policy of U.S. multinational corporations. Results indicated that there are several sources of morale problems existing in multinational corporations of the dominant type. These included blocked promotions, transfer anxieties, income gaps, and unfamiliarity and adaptability difficulties. The research also indicates that the accumulation of variegated international experience is not essentially translated into managerial behavior compatible with environmental needs and headquarter's expectations.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/255406
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/255406
